🌐 Newtonian Inertia Engine

A real-time, 3D telemetry visualization dashboard for the Raspberry Pi using the ICM20948 9-DOF motion sensor (commonly found on the Waveshare Environment HAT). This interface displays live pitch/roll, total G-force, rotational velocity, and magnetic strength in a custom Tkinter GUI.
🛠️ Hardware Requirements

    Raspberry Pi (Tested on Pi 4 / Pi 5)

    Waveshare Environment HAT (or any ICM20948 breakout board connected via I2C)

    Shutterstock


(Note: If you are using a standalone sensor instead of the HAT, connect SDA to Pin 3, SCL to Pin 5, 3V3 to Pin 1, and GND to Pin 6).
🚀 Quickstart Guide
Step 1: Enable I2C on your Raspberry Pi

The sensor communicates with the Pi over I2C, which is disabled by default.

    Open your terminal and run the configuration tool:
    Bash

    sudo raspi-config

    Navigate to Interface Options -> I2C.

    Select Yes to enable the ARM I2C interface.

    Exit the tool and reboot your Pi if prompted.

Step 2: Install System Dependencies

Tkinter (the framework used for the GUI) requires a system-level package to run properly on Raspberry Pi OS. Run the following command:
Bash

sudo apt update
sudo apt install python3-tk python3-venv -y

Step 3: Set Up a Virtual Environment

To keep your Pi's Python environment clean and avoid installation errors, create a virtual environment inside your project folder:
Bash

# Create a folder for the project and navigate into it
mkdir newtonian-engine
cd newtonian-engine

# Create the virtual environment
python3 -m venv env

# Activate the virtual environment
source env/bin/activate

(Note: You will need to run the source env/bin/activate command every time you open a new terminal to work on this project).
Step 4: Install Python Libraries

With your virtual environment activated, install the required packages. We are using adafruit-blinka to allow the Pi to use CircuitPython libraries, and customtkinter for the dark-mode UI.
Bash

pip install customtkinter matplotlib numpy adafruit-blinka adafruit-circuitpython-icm20x

Step 5: Run the Engine

    Download the main.py file from this repository and place it in your project folder.

    Run the script:

Bash

python main.py

    Tilt your Raspberry Pi to watch the 3D globe and telemetry data update in real-time! If you bump or spin the Pi too hard, watch out for the KINETIC DISRUPTION warning!

🛑 Troubleshooting

    Motion Sensor Error: No I2C device at address: 0x68
    Make sure your HAT is pressed firmly onto the GPIO pins, or your standalone sensor is wired correctly. Ensure I2C is enabled (Step 1).

    The GUI opens but the numbers are static and say -0.07
    The app has entered "Simulation Mode" because it cannot detect the sensor. Double-check your hardware connections.

    ModuleNotFoundError: No module named 'tkinter'
    You skipped Step 2! Make sure to run sudo apt install python3-tk.
